\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Soqucoin System Architecture. The flow demonstrates how Dilithium signatures are aggregated via PAT into a Merkle-tree commitment (root size 65–72 bytes), then optionally folded into a succinct LatticeFold+ proof (constant $\sim $1.38 kB) by an off-chain prover (e.g., transaction creator or mining pool). The block includes the proof in a transaction script (typically the coinbase or vin[0]), with the transaction Merkle root in the block header. This enables constant-time $O(1)$ verification by nodes using the \texttt  {OP\_CHECKFOLDPROOF} opcode, with soundness error bounded by $2^{-130}$ (Theorem 4.2, \cite  {latticefold2025}).}}{2}{figure.caption.1}\protected@file@percent }
\providecommand*\caption@xref[2]{\@setref\relax\@undefined{#1}}
\newlabel{fig:architecture}{{1}{2}{Soqucoin System Architecture. The flow demonstrates how Dilithium signatures are aggregated via PAT into a Merkle-tree commitment (root size 65–72 bytes), then optionally folded into a succinct LatticeFold+ proof (constant $\sim $1.38 kB) by an off-chain prover (e.g., transaction creator or mining pool). The block includes the proof in a transaction script (typically the coinbase or vin[0]), with the transaction Merkle root in the block header. This enables constant-time $O(1)$ verification by nodes using the \texttt {OP\_CHECKFOLDPROOF} opcode, with soundness error bounded by $2^{-130}$ (Theorem 4.2, \cite {latticefold2025})}{figure.caption.1}{}}
